I took to the sea on a ship called "Victoria". Victoria was once part of the proud navy of Denmark. It was a first-class ship", indeed". The ocean passages were drawn-out. We spent most of the Summer in Cosmonauts Sea. The ocean passages were dull. I had many friends among the crew. One of them, Roger, had fought in the Anglo-Spanish War.

But I had gotten enough of the seas so I went ashore to find work. I didn't have very much luck. It made me dispirited.

It was the year 1727 when I started working as a builder.

When I was 27 I lost my job. I dropped a cup of tea on my boss's wife actually.

She had been badly damaged in the Seven Years' War. We specialized in pirating on the Banda Sea. . I had many friends among the crew. One of them, Judy, could lift 100 pounds. We spent most of the Autumn in Barents Sea. We had to sail with reefed sails for much of the journey. The seas were high and the weather was windy.

But I had gotten enough of the seas so I went ashore to find work. I didn't have very much luck.

""I could always return to the seas"", I thought as I boarded "Revenge", a rough around the edges sloop. It was a contemptible looking ship. It was said that she had been through fourteen storms. Our objective was atlantic trading. We were smuggling porcelain from Prussia. We had to cross the Greenland Sea. There was a large amount of champagne drunk during this trip and there was plenty of fighting. The first mate was called Evans.Evans was as considerate as he was objective.

But I had gotten enough of the seas so I went ashore to find work. I didn't have very much luck. It made me feel moderately forgetful.

Louis Gonzales

I was born on a bright day in November.

One thing happened when I was 6: I grew older and older. I thought a lot about the mystery of dilemma of George Washington.

I had to find employment.

I was 21 when I married Amy. I started going more and more to Church and studied the bible closely.

""I wonder where this will take me"", I thought as I boarded the "Emma", a ketch from Portugal. The ship was originally built in Philadelphia for the purpose of atlantic trading. She was commanded and officered by high-class sailors and educated gentlemen. We had to sail with reefed sails for much of the journey. I had many fellows among the crew. One of them, Eleonor, had once seen and spoken to Friedrich Schiller. We passed many unyoung ports. They said our ship had once brought Denis Diderot home.

When I was 25 my son Ariel were born.

I was rather fed up with sailing by 1780 so I tried to find a job on land.

"I wanted to try my luck on the salt seas!" It was the "Queen of India", a ketch from Hispaniola. Queen of India was once part of the proud navy of Italy. The ship itself was built from white oak logs. The crew was rather old. We passed many ancient ports. The seas were high and the weather was cold. We had to sail with reefed sails for much of the journey. However, I had many friends among the crew. One of them, Abner, in Cadiz had married a woman from Ethiopia who soon after the wedding disappeared.

It was the year I turned 30 that my son Clemens were born. It appeared comparatively contradictory to me.

The End.

It was in September 1735 that I became a woman. It made me moody.

It was in August 1736 that I married. I started working as a rowing lady.

Much later my eldest boy Roger were born.

I got older and one day lightning struck me! I almost died! I promise!

The End.

Ernest Wells

I was born on a rainy day in December in 1758. after I was born, were left motherless.

I went ahead and tried to get a job.

It was in October 1774 that I started working as a sailor.

The End.

Emelie Output

Adeline Wilson

I was born in dark Westhoughton in 1774.

Several years after that I grew older and older. I loved to read, especially "Songs of Innocence and of Experience ".

When I was 17 I became a woman. I started working as a maid.

But as the years passed I found guidance in the Lord.

It was the year 1737 when I became pregnant and had twins named Emma and Karen.

In 1753 something special happened: lightning struck me! I almost died! You have my word of honor!

One thing happened when I was 60: I fell in love with Francis.

The End.

Edward Wood

I come from Skelmersdale. When I grew up my dad taught me all about his trade as a butcher. I used to row my boat to the market.

I went ahead and tried to get a job.

Much later Eleonor, my wife, and I married.

Much later I was low that I had to get a job as a cartwright.

After a couple of years, I became a father.

But as the years passed my daughter Charlotte were born.

The End.

Sean Ross

I was born in warm Gosport in 1777. after I was born, were left motherless.

It was in May 1739 that I realised I had to go and search for employment. It was toilsome.

It was the year 1741 when I married Ruth.

Years later, I started working as a gambler.

When I was 39 I became a father.

It was in December 1777 that and I got a phenomenal little kid named Valentin.

The End.

Bonnie Cowell

I come from Huntingdon.

Once I went to the doctor and he told me I had herpes. I ate medicine and lay in bed for the whole Winter and I almost deceased. I am fortunately a bit better now. .

It was the year I turned 6 that I grew older and older. I used to row my boat to the market.

It was the year I turned 17 that I became a woman. It made me feel pretty well-bred.

The End.

Carmen Kim

I come from Leiston. I was so unfortunate as to be the youngest of five children of our mother, who was a childhood friend of King George III.

A long time later I turned into an adult.

Several years after that I married. I will never forget the year 1737, for that was when I met the awesome Richard.He made me lively unlike no one else.

When I was 29 I gave birth to my eldest girl Josephine. I started working as a baker. It made me melanchoic.

Much later I found guidance in the Lord.

The End.

Ruth Wesley

I was born in this very town, in the good year of 1775. I was adopted into the family of my father’s younger brother, when my father was betrayed and imprisoned.

I was 11 when my dear friend George passed away. He had a pleasant countenance, and easy, unaffected manners.

The End.

Maurice Rowling

I was born in windy Hednesford in 1781.

Do you know about pneumonia? I didn't until I was 1 and got it. I ate medicine and lay in bed for the whole Winter. Unfortunately it only made me feel worse. But then I tried something else: I went to get some fresh air in South Kirkby and Moorthorpe. That worked and now I am as healthy as ever!. My childhood was rather free and easy. My dad had once been a catholic.

I had to find employment.

A long time later I was fed up that I had to get a job as a soldier in the royal army.

One thing happened when I was 33: I became a father", the mother was a girl called "Broomhilda. when my dear friend, passed away I was still comparatively a young man--still confident, sociable and planful-

Years later, I became a father", the mother was a girl called "Angelina.

The End.

Lucy Benton

I come from Ulverston. When I grew up my dad taught me all about his trade as a courier. I used to visit the fort and look for the bargemans and mapmakers.

It was in April 1725 that I turned into an adult.

A long time later I married Richard. It made me feel quite challenging. I started working as a maid.

Months and years passed but suddenly Richard, my precious old comrade, gave up the ghost.

The End.

Jack Baden

I was born on a sunny day in March. I was adopted into the family of my father’s younger brother, when my father was betrayed and imprisoned.

When I was 16 my illegitimate son Will were born.

I went ahead and tried to get a job.

When I was 19 I got a job as a smith.

I was 19 when I found guidance in the Lord.

It was then it occurred: my superb Carmen was born!

The End.

Anne Riddington

I was born on a cold day in October. I was adopted into the family of my father’s younger brother, when my father was betrayed and imprisoned.

One thing happened when I was 6: I found god.

I was 17 when I wasn't a child anymore.

When I was 23 I got married to Maurice. I liked that he was so educated. I started working as a midwife. It made me feel rather scholarly.

Suddenly, on a beautiful sunday, Jim, my good long-lived friend, kicked the bucket.

It was the year I turned 34 that I became a mother for the first time. It was a girl called Elisabeth.

The End.

Aurora Lois

I come from Ramsgate.

Several years after that I grew older and older. Every monday I went to the church.

But as the years passed I turned into an adult. It made me feel pretty extravagant. I started working as a rowing lady. It made me fed up. nName was a handsome girl, and an affectionate mentor. She was my world back then.

A extraordinary thing happened when I was 35 - I forged the handwriting of Johann Wolfgang von Goethe. I had to spend one months in prison. You probably don't believe it but it's true!

The End.

Anna Preston

I was born in this very town, in the good year of 1756. I was forced to polish the shoes of rich gentlemen to make some money. In 1770 I would have solved the Assurance mystery if it wasn't for my dull, chuckleheaded friend.

Several years after that I wasn't a child anymore. It made me unconstrained. I started working as a baker.

The End.

I come from Honiton.

The End.

Years later, I had to face reality and take a job as a baker.

Elisabeth Smith

I was born on a foggy day in December. My big interest was drawing with charcoal.

Much later I became a woman.

I was 19 when I married Pete. I will never forget the year 1737, for that was when I met the high-class Simon.Simon was good-looking and gentlemanlike.

It was the year I turned 29 that I became pregnant and had twins named Colin and Mary. I started working as a rowing lady.

I got older and one day the most important thing happened - I discovered Jesus. I assure you!

The End.

Gerald Mills

I come from Nantwich. My father was a trader and my mother a baker.

Much later my good benefactor Jeremiah departed.

After a couple of years, I realised I had to go and search for employment. It was toilsome.

I was 27 when my illegitimate son Jeremy were born.

A long time later I started working as a shopkeeper.

Years later, Lucy, my wife, and I married.

Do you know about herpes? I didn't until I was 31 and got it. I had to get rid of my hound, and I felt my strength returning. .

But on the 17 of December 1729 the most astonishing thing happened - my fabulous Agatha was born!when my precious partner, deceased I was still comparatively a young man--still witty, impressive and conciliatory-

When I was 61 I found god.

When I was 61 I became a father.

When I was 68 and I got a terrific little kid named Leon. I will never forget the year 1779, for that was when I met the splendid Caitlin.She was relaxed anf active.

The End.
